    <subfield code="a">Since the early 2000s physicists have developed an ingenious but non-rigorous formalism called the cavity method to put forward precise conjectures on phase transitions in random problems (Mézard et al., 2002 [37] ). The cavity method predicts that the satisfiability threshold in the random k -SAT problem is <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mtext>-</mtext><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">SAT</mi></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant="normal">ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>ε</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub></math> , with <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">lim</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><mo>∞</mo></mrow></msub><mo>⁡</mo><msub><mrow><mi>ε</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> (Mertens et al., 2006 [35] ). This paper contains a proof of the conjecture.</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">Elsevier</subfield>
